The chart presents data on opinions regarding the influence of the Quran on national laws across different countries.
In Pakistan, a majority of 78% believe that laws should strictly follow the teachings of the Quran, which is the highest percentage among the listed countries for this viewpoint.
In contrast, Lebanon has the highest percentage (60%) of respondents who believe that laws should not be influenced by the Quran.
As for those who think that laws should follow the values and principles of Islam but not strictly follow the Quran, Burkina Faso has the highest percentage at 36%.
Looking at the middle category of following values and principles of Islam, but not strictly, Malaysia stands out with a substantial 52%, which is the highest among the sampled countries.
Meanwhile, Jordan and Senegal have significant percentages for both strictly following (54% and 49%, respectively) and following values and principles (38% and 33%, respectively).
The presented percentages are based on the share of the sample in each country that identifies as Muslim, with the percentages varying from 50% in Nigeria to 100% in Palestine.
Notably, this data includes full country samples and encompasses both Muslim and non-Muslim responses.
The source of the information is the Spring 2015 Global Attitudes Survey, Question 24, by the Pew Research Center.

The graph shows the number of racially motivated hate crimes in England and Wales from April 2019 to March 2020, by region.
The regions are listed on the x-axis, and the number of hate crimes is listed on the y-axis.
The highest number of racially motivated hate crimes occurred in London, with 15,367 offenses.
This was followed by the West Midlands (10,882 offenses), Greater Manchester (8,982 offenses), and Yorkshire and the Humber (8,318 offenses).
The lowest number of racially motivated hate crimes occurred in Wales, with 3,171 offenses.
There is a clear regional variation in the number of racially motivated hate crimes.
The regions with the highest populations also have the highest number of hate crimes.
However, the rate of hate crimes per capita is also higher in some regions, such as London and the West Midlands.
It is important to note that this graph only shows the number of racially motivated hate crimes that were reported to the police.
It is estimated that many hate crimes go unreported.

The chart presents data on Americans' views of other countries, categorizing opinions as either "Percent Unfavorable" or "Favorable."

Overall, the data indicates a trend where traditional allies such as Canada and Great Britain are viewed most favorably, while attitudes towards other nations, particularly Mexico, China, Russia, and Saudi Arabia, are comparatively less favorable among Americans.

Chart Description

The chart shows the percentage of news coverage devoted to each of the following topics:

 Health care reform
 Economy
 Afghanistan
 Obama's Nobel Prize
 Climate change conference
 Pakistani arrests

The chart also shows the percentage of people who named each story as the most closely followed.

Statistics and Relations

 Extrema:
     The highest percentage of news coverage was devoted to health care reform (14%), followed by the economy (16%).
The highest percentage of people who named a story as the most closely followed was for health care reform (31%), followed by the economy (19%).

Relationships:
     There is a general positive correlation between news coverage and interest, but there are some exceptions.
For example, Obama's Nobel Prize received relatively low news coverage (9%), but it was named as the most closely followed story by 9% of people.
The topics with the highest news coverage (health care reform and the economy) are also the topics with the highest interest.

Conclusion

The chart shows that there is a relationship between news coverage and interest, but this relationship is not perfect.
Some stories receive more news coverage than others, but they may not be the stories that people are most interested in.

The chart presents data on technology use among U.S. adults aged 75 and up, based on a survey conducted from September 29 to November 6, 2016, as reported by the Pew Research Center.
The information is divided into three categories: use of the internet, subscription to home broadband services, and ownership of a smartphone.
For internet use, the highest percentage is seen in the 65-69 age group, with 82% of individuals reporting that they use the internet.
This percentage decreases with age, with 75% of those aged 70-74, 60% of those 75-79, and only 44% of individuals who are 80 or older using the internet.
Subscriptions to home broadband services follow a similar pattern.
66% of the 65-69 age group subscribe to these services, making them the most connected group.
Subscriptions drop to 61% for the 70-74 age group, further decline to 41% for those aged 75-79, and reach the lowest at 28% for individuals 80 or older.
Smartphone ownership also decreases with age.
The 65-69 age group leads with 59% owning a smartphone.
Ownership drops to 49% among those aged 70-74, then to 31% for individuals 75-79, and reaches the lowest level at 17% for those aged 80 or above.

Rwanda Budget Balance in Relation to GDP

Overview:

The line graph shows Rwanda's budget balance in relation to GDP from 2015 to 2025.
The budget balance is the difference between government revenue and expenditure.
A positive budget balance indicates that the government is running a surplus, while a negative budget balance indicates that the government is running a deficit.

Key Findings:

 Rwanda's budget balance has been consistently negative throughout the period shown in the graph.
The largest deficit occurred in 2020, at -6.4% of GDP.
This was due to the COVID-19 pandemic, which led to a sharp decline in government revenue and an increase in government expenditure.
The deficit is projected to decrease gradually in the coming years, reaching -2.87% of GDP in 2028.

Extrema:

 The largest deficit occurred in 2020, at -6.4% of GDP.
The smallest deficit occurred in 2017, at -1.2% of GDP.

Relations:

 The budget balance is closely correlated with GDP growth.

Line graph showing sales of tea worldwide by region from 2008 to 2019 in million euros

The line graph shows the sales of tea worldwide by region from 2008 to 2019 in million euros.
The graph shows that the sales of tea in Europe have been the highest throughout the period, followed by Asia and North America.
The sales of tea in all three regions have increased over time, but the rate of growth has been fastest in Asia.
The sales of tea in Europe reached a peak of 800 million euros in 2018, before declining slightly in 2019.
The sales of tea in Asia have grown steadily from 2008 to 2019, reaching 600 million euros in 2019.
The sales of tea in North America have also grown steadily over the period, reaching 400 million euros in 2019.
Overall, the line graph shows that the sales of tea worldwide have been increasing over time, with Europe being the largest market for tea.
The sales of tea in Asia are growing at the fastest rate, and are expected to surpass the sales of tea in Europe in the near future.

The chart presents two categories of data regarding U.S. adults' perception of the Supreme Court based on their political inclination, either as Republicans/Lean Republican or Democrats/Lean Democrat.

A minority, 8% in total, believe the Supreme Court has too little power; this view is more prevalent among Democrats/Lean Democrats (11%) compared to Republicans/Lean Republicans (6%).
The second category addresses the ideological stance of the current Supreme Court.
Overall, 56% of U.S. adults consider it to be "Middle of the road," with Republicans/Lean Republicans being the majority in this group at 66%.
In contrast, Democrats/Lean Democrats are split, with 47% labeling the Supreme Court as "Conservative" and another 47% as "Middle of the road."
Only 12% of the total participants find the court "Liberal," with a higher proportion of Republicans/Lean Republicans (20%) compared to Democrats/Lean Democrats (4%).

Chart Description

The chart shows the percentage of respondents identifying with the Democratic and Republican parties in the United States, as measured by low-response-rate phone surveys and high-response-rate in-person surveys.
The data is from the General Social Survey (GSS) and Pew Research Center surveys from 1990 to 2016.

Key Statistics and Relations

 Extrema: The percentage of respondents identifying as Democrats has remained relatively stable over time, ranging from 31% to 35%.
The percentage of respondents identifying as Republicans has fluctuated more, ranging from 23% to 32%.
Relationship: The two sets of data show a similar pattern, with Democrats consistently outnumbering Republicans.
However, the phone surveys tend to show a slightly larger Democratic advantage.

Perceptual and Cognitive Phenomena

 Visual appearance: The chart is visually striking, with the two lines for Democrats and Republicans diverging over time.
This suggests that the partisan divide in the United States is growing.
Cognitive salience: The chart makes the partisan divide in the United States highly salient.
This is because it shows the data over a long period of time and compares two different survey methods.

Chart Description:

This chart shows public opinion on the likelihood of three outcomes of U.S. airstrikes in Syria: creating a backlash against the U.S. and its allies in the region, leading to a long-term military commitment there, and being effective in discouraging the use of chemical weapons.

Statistics:

 Most Americans (74%) believe that U.S. airstrikes in Syria are likely to create a backlash against the U.S. and its allies in the region.
About two-thirds of Americans (61%) believe that U.S. airstrikes in Syria are likely to lead to a long-term military commitment there.
Only about one-third of Americans (33%) believe that U.S. airstrikes in Syria are likely to be effective in discouraging the use of chemical weapons.

Relationships:

 There is a strong correlation between the belief that U.S. airstrikes in Syria are likely to create a backlash and the belief that they are likely to lead to a long-term military commitment.

There is a weaker correlation between the belief that U.S. airstrikes in Syria are likely to create a backlash and the belief that they are likely to be effective in discouraging the use of chemical weapons.

There is a weak correlation between the belief that U.S. airstrikes in Syria are likely to lead to a long-term military commitment and the belief that they are likely to be effective in discouraging the use of chemical weapons.

Conclusion:

Overall, the public is skeptical of the potential benefits of U.S. airstrikes in Syria and is more concerned about the potential negative consequences.

Chart Title: Opinion of Economy, EU on the Rise

Chart Description:

The chart shows the median opinion of the economy, economic integration, and EU among six EU member states from 2012 to 2015.

Perceptual and Cognitive Phenomena:

 The chart is visually striking, with a clear upward trend in all three measures of opinion.
The trend is particularly pronounced for the measure of favorable view of the EU.
This suggests that public opinion of the EU economy and its integration has been improving significantly in recent years.

Statistics and Relations:

 The median favorable view of the EU reached 61% in 2015, up from 32% in 2012.
The median view that economic integration has strengthened the economy rose from 21% to 46% over the same period.
The median view that the economy is good increased from 12% to 28%.
Overall, the chart shows a clear and positive trend in public opinion of the EU economy and its integration.

Additional Notes:

 It is worth noting that the chart only shows the median opinion of six EU member states.
It is possible that public opinion in other EU member states has not improved as much, or even declined.

Chart Description:

This chart shows the percentage of U.S. adults who say that the use of anonymous sources has a great deal (21%) or some (47%) influence on whether they think news stories are credible, broken down by their views on the acceptability of anonymous sources in news stories.

Key Statistics:

 Overall: 68% of U.S. adults say that anonymous sources in a story have a great deal of (21%) or some (47%) influence on how they evaluate a story's credibility.

By acceptability of anonymous sources:
     Always acceptable: 14% say that the use of anonymous sources has a great deal of influence on their trust in a news story, while 46% say it has some influence.
Only acceptable in special cases: 15% say that the use of anonymous sources has a great deal of influence on their trust in a news story, while 56% say it has some influence.
Never acceptable: 49% say that the use of anonymous sources has a great deal of influence on their trust in a news story, while 25% say it has some influence.

Perceptual and Cognitive Phenomena:

The chart shows a clear trend that people who oppose the use of anonymous sources are more likely to say that it has a negative impact on their trust in news stories.
This suggests that people may be more likely to be skeptical of stories that rely on anonymous sources, even if they contain accurate information.

Another perceptual phenomenon that is worth noting is the difference in the perceived impact of anonymous sources between those who say they are always acceptable and those who say they are only acceptable in special cases.

Those who say anonymous sources are always acceptable are less likely to say that they have a negative impact on trust in news stories, even though they are using the same scale to rate their influence.
This suggests that people may have different thresholds for what they consider to be an acceptable level of reliance on anonymous sources.

Chart Description

The chart shows the percentage of U.S. adults who say that local journalists/news media are in touch with the community, mostly cover the area where they live, and have a lot of influence.

Key Statistics and Relationships

 Extrema: Democrats are more likely than Republicans to say that local news media are connected to the community (67% vs. 61%), mostly cover the area where they live (54% vs. 49%), and have a lot of influence (40% vs. 34%).
Trends: There is a general trend towards lower ratings for all three measures of connection, coverage, and influence.
For example, the percentage of people who say that local news media are in touch with the community has decreased from 72% in 2012 to 61% in 2018.

Perceptual and Cognitive Phenomena

The chart may be perceived differently by people with different political affiliations.
For example, Republicans may be more likely to focus on the lower ratings for local news media, while Democrats may be more likely to focus on the higher ratings.
The chart may also be cognitively challenging to interpret, as it shows three different measures of connection, coverage, and influence.
This can make it difficult to see the overall trends in the data.

Overall Summary

The chart shows that there is a partisan divide in perceptions of local news media.
Democrats are more likely than Republicans to say that local news media are connected to the community, mostly cover the area where they live, and have a lot of influence.

The chart titled "American Incomes Are Losing Their Edge, Except at the Top" demonstrates the inflation-adjusted, after-tax income over time for various income percentiles in the United States.

The chart provides evidence that the stock market has outperformed the housing market during the economic recovery.

It is important to note that the stock market and the housing market are two different asset classes, and they are subject to different forces.

The chart is titled "Democrats with high science knowledge have more confidence in the scientific method" and presents data on the percentage of U.S. adults in various groups who have differing views on the scientific method.
It distinguishes between the overall population, categorized by political affiliation and level of science knowledge.
For U.S. adults in general, 35% believe the scientific method can be used to produce any conclusion the researcher wants, while a majority of 63% believe it generally produces accurate conclusions.

Among Republicans, as the level of science knowledge increases from low to high, the belief that the scientific method can be used to produce any conclusion the researcher wants also increases from 48% to 40%.
However, confidence in the scientific method producing accurate conclusions decreases from 51% among those with low science knowledge to 59% among those with high science knowledge.
In contrast, among Democrats, there is a notable different pattern.

As the level of science knowledge increases, the belief in the scientific method being manipulated to produce any desired conclusion decreases, going from 46% for those with low science knowledge to 14% for those with high science knowledge.
Concurrently, the belief in accurately producing conclusions increases substantially, from 52% among those with low science knowledge to 86% among those with high science knowledge.
Overall, Democrats with high science knowledge exhibit the most confidence in the scientific method producing accurate conclusions.

The chart suggests a distinction in the perception of the scientific method between individuals with varying levels of science knowledge and across political affiliations, with a clear trend that higher science knowledge correlates with more confidence in the scientific method among Democrats.

Chart Description:

The chart shows the number of mergers and acquisitions (M&A) transactions in the United Kingdom (UK) by city or region in 2018 and 2019.

The South East was the second most active region, followed by the Midlands and North West.
The least active regions for M&A activity were Wales and Northern Ireland.
Overall, M&A activity increased in the UK in 2019, with over 2,500 transactions completed, compared to just over 2,300 transactions in 2018.

Extrema:

 The highest number of M&A transactions in any city or region in 2018 and 2019 was in London, with 1,581 transactions in 2018 and 1,623 transactions in 2019.
The lowest number of M&A transactions in any city or region in 2018 and 2019 was in Northern Ireland, with 38 transactions in 2018 and 41 transactions in 2019.

Relations:

 There is a clear correlation between the size of a city or region and its level of M&A activity.
London is the largest city and economic hub in the UK, and it is also the most active region for M&A.
The South East, Midlands, and North West are also major economic regions in the UK, and they rank as the second, third, and fourth most active regions for M&A activity, respectively.

Line graph of CVS Health's revenue distribution from 2015 to 2025, by product group

This line graph shows the revenue distribution of CVS Health from 2015 to 2025, by product group.
The y-axis shows the percentage of revenue generated by each product group, while the x-axis shows the year.

The three product groups are:

 Pharmacy services: This product group includes prescription drugs, over-the-counter medications, and other pharmacy-related products and services.
Front store: This product group includes non-pharmacy items, such as health and beauty products, food and beverages, and general merchandise.
Other: This product group includes all other revenue, such as revenue from MinuteClinic and pharmacy benefits management (PBM) services.

Key observations:

 Pharmacy services is the largest product group, accounting for over 70% of CVS Health's revenue in 2015.
Front store revenue has remained relatively flat over the past decade, accounting for around 20% of total revenue.
Other revenue has grown steadily over the past decade, accounting for around 10% of total revenue in 2025.
The overall revenue distribution of CVS Health has remained relatively stable over the past decade, with pharmacy services accounting for the majority of revenue.

Extrema:

 The highest percentage of revenue generated by pharmacy services was 72.5% in 2015.

The chart displays public opinion on whether the current Congress is more productive, less productive, or the same in comparison to recent Congresses.

The data covers a period from 1994 to 2016, with markings at two-year intervals that correspond to different presidencies marked by the initials of Presidents Clinton (D), Bush (R), Obama (D), and Trump (R), alongside the partisan control of the Senate and House of Representatives during those periods.

Key observations include:
- The percentage of Americans who believe Congress is "less" productive peaks at 55% in 2014 during Obama's presidency.
- The sentiment that Congress is "more" productive hits its lowest at 8% at four distinct points in 1994, 2002, 2010, and 2016.
- Throughout the entire period, the majority opinion has never considered Congress to be "more" productive than the past, with the highest percentage reaching only 18% in 2008.
- The percentage of people who think Congress is "the same" starts at 51% in 1994 and sees a downward trend to 33% in 2016.

- The public opinion fluctuates over time with respect to the "less" productive and "same" categories, showing no clear long-term trend correlating with the changes in presidency or the control of the Senate and House.

Chart Title: Value added of U.S. motor vehicle and parts manufacturing as a percentage of GDP between 2005 and 2017

Chart Type: Line graph

Data:

| Year | Value added as a percentage of GDP |
|---|---|
| 2005 | 0.94% |
| 2006 | 0.97% |
| 2007 | 0.96% |
| 2008 | 0.63% |
| 2009 | 0.49% |
| 2010 | 0.67% |
| 2011 | 0.75% |
| 2012 | 0.78% |
| 2013 | 0.83% |
| 2014 | 0.85% |
| 2015 | 0.90% |
| 2016 | 0.91% |
| 2017 | 0.89% |

Summary:

The chart shows the value added of U.S. motor vehicle and parts manufacturing as a percentage of GDP between 2005 and 2017.
The value added of motor vehicle manufacturing declined sharply during the Great Recession, but recovered in the following years.
However, it remained below its pre-recession level throughout the period shown.

Extrema:

The highest value added of motor vehicle manufacturing as a percentage of GDP was 0.97% in 2006.
The lowest value added was 0.49% in 2009.

Relations:

The value added of motor vehicle manufacturing is closely related to the overall health of the U.S. economy.
When the economy is strong, demand for vehicles is high, and the motor vehicle manufacturing sector thrives.
Conversely, when the economy is weak, demand for vehicles declines, and the motor vehicle manufacturing sector suffers.

Conclusion:

The motor vehicle manufacturing sector is an important part of the U.S. economy.
However, its importance has declined somewhat in recent years.

Chart Description

The chart shows the percentage of Americans who say that each of the following bothers them about the federal tax system:

 Some corporations don't pay their fair share
 Some wealthy people don't pay their fair share
 The complexity of the tax system
 The amount you pay in taxes
 Some poor people don't pay their fair share

Statistics and Relations

 The most common complaint is that some corporations don't pay their fair share, with 62% of Americans saying that this bothers them either a lot or some.
The second most common complaint is that some wealthy people don't pay their fair share, with 60% of Americans saying that this bothers them either a lot or some.
The third most common complaint is that the tax system is too complex, with 43% of Americans saying that this bothers them either a lot or some.
The fourth most common complaint is that the amount you pay in taxes bothers Americans, with 27% saying that this bothers them either a lot or some.
The least common complaint is that some poor people don't pay their fair share, with only 20% of Americans saying that this bothers them either a lot or some.

Extrema

 The highest percentage of Americans who say that something bothers them about the tax system is 62% for corporations not paying their fair share.
The lowest percentage of Americans who say that something bothers them about the tax system is 20% for poor people not paying their fair share.

Conclusion

The chart shows that the most common complaints about the federal tax system are that some corporations and wealthy people don't pay their fair share, and that the tax system is too complex.
These findings suggest that Americans believe that the tax system is not fair, and that it is difficult to navigate.

The chart presents the percentage of different generations' views on the impact of same-sex and interracial marriages on society.

For same-sex marriage, the majority agreement that it's a "good thing" for society decreases with each older generation: Gen Z has the highest agreement at 48%, followed by Millennials at 47%, Gen X at 33%, Boomers at 27%, and the Silent generation at 18%.

Conversely, the view that same-sex marriage is a "bad thing" for society increases with older generations: 15% of both Gen Z and Millennials, 25% of Gen X, 32% of Boomers, and 43% of the Silent generation hold this view.

In terms of neutrality, where respondents believe same-sex marriage "doesn't make a difference" to society, Gen X leads with 41%, followed closely by Boomers with 40%, then Silent generation with 38%, Millennials with 37%, and Gen Z with 36%.
Regarding interracial marriage, the pattern is similar; the younger generations, Gen Z and Millennials, both show the highest approval with 53% each stating it is a "good thing" for society.
Approval rates decrease with older generations: Gen X at 41%, Boomers at 30%, and the Silent generation at 20%.

The perception that interracial marriage is a "bad thing" for society follows an ascending trend with age: 4% for both Gen Z and Millennials, 5% for Gen X, 10% for Boomers, and 14% for the Silent generation.

Concerning the opinion that interracial marriage "doesn't make a difference," Boomers and the Silent generation have the largest percentages at 60% and 66%, respectively, followed by Gen X at 53%, then Gen Z and Millennials both at 43%.
It should be noted that the share of respondents who did not offer an answer is not represented in the chart.
The data source is surveys conducted with U.S. adults aged 18 and older from September 24 to October 7, 2018, and U.S. teens aged 13 to 17 from September 17 to November 25, 2018.

Chart Description

The chart shows the percentage of U.S. adults who favor the death penalty for persons convicted of murder from 1996 to 2018.

Statistics

 Maximum: 78% (1996)
 Minimum: 54% (2018)
 Average: 66%

Relationships

 Support for the death penalty has declined over time, from a high of 78% in 1996 to 54% in 2018.
However, there was a slight uptick in support in 2018.

Interpretation

The decline in support for the death penalty suggests that Americans are becoming more skeptical of capital punishment.
This may be due to a number of factors, including concerns about the fairness of the death penalty system, the high cost of executions, and the possibility of executing innocent people.
The slight uptick in support in 2018 may be due to a number of factors, such as the high-profile cases of mass shootings and other violent crimes.
However, it is too early to say whether this represents a lasting trend.

Income level also influences concern levels.

Summary of Cambodia Life Expectancy at Birth from 2008 to 2018

The line chart shows the life expectancy at birth in Cambodia from 2008 to 2018.
The life expectancy increased steadily from 60.1 years in 2008 to 69.2 years in 2018, an increase of 9.1 years over the decade.
The life expectancy in Cambodia is relatively low compared to other countries in the region, but it has improved significantly in recent years.
This improvement is likely due to a number of factors, including improved access to healthcare, reduced child mortality, and better nutrition.

Extrema

The highest life expectancy at birth in Cambodia during the period 2008-2018 was 69.2 years in 2018.
The lowest life expectancy at birth was 60.1 years in 2008.

Relationships

The life expectancy at birth in Cambodia shows a strong positive correlation with time.
This means that as time increases, the life expectancy also increases.

Conclusion

The life expectancy at birth in Cambodia has improved significantly in recent years.
However, it is still relatively low compared to other countries in the region.

Graph Title: Republican Party Now Viewed Negatively in Tea Party Districts

Graph Description:

This graph shows the percentage of adults in the United States who have a favorable or unfavorable view of the Republican Party, broken down by whether they live in a Tea Party district.

The graph shows that, over time, the percentage of adults in Tea Party districts with an unfavorable view of the Republican Party has increased, while the percentage with a favorable view has decreased.

Statistical Highlights:

 The highest percentage of adults in Tea Party districts with an unfavorable view of the Republican Party was 49% in October 2011.
The lowest percentage of adults in Tea Party districts with an unfavorable view of the Republican Party was 34% in September 2010.
The highest percentage of adults in Tea Party districts with a favorable view of the Republican Party was 55% in September 2010.
The lowest percentage of adults in Tea Party districts with a favorable view of the Republican Party was 41% in October 2011.

Perceptual and Cognitive Phenomena:

The graph is visually striking because of the sharp contrast between the two lines.

The line representing the percentage of adults in Tea Party districts with an unfavorable view of the Republican Party is consistently above the line representing the percentage of adults in the general public with an unfavorable view of the Republican Party.
This suggests that there is a significant difference in public opinion about the Republican Party between Tea Party districts and the general public.
The graph also suggests that public opinion about the Republican Party in Tea Party districts is becoming increasingly negative.

The population is divided into three age groups: 0-14 years, 15-64 years, and 65 years and over.
The population in the 0-14 age group decreased steadily from 1990 to 2019, from 284 million to 254 million.
This is due to China's one-child policy, which was in effect from 1979 to 2015.
The population in the 15-64 age group increased from 675 million in 1990 to 950 million in 2019.
This is the largest age group in China, and it is the group that is most productive in the workforce.
The population in the 65 years and over age group increased from 62 million in 1990 to 144 million in 2019.
This is the fastest-growing age group in China, and it is due to the country's aging population.

The fastest-growing population group from 1990 to 2019 was the 65 years and over age group.

The line graph shows the urbanization of Syria from 2009 to 2019.
The share of urban population in total population increased from 52.9% in 2009 to 55.4% in 2019.
The rate of urbanization was relatively slow between 2009 and 2011, but it accelerated after the start of the Syrian Civil War in 2011.
The fastest rate of urbanization occurred between 2014 and 2016, when the share of urban population increased by 1.6 percentage points per year.
The rate of urbanization slowed down in 2017 and 2018, but it remained higher than the pre-war level.

The increase in the share of urban population in Syria was driven by a number of factors, including rural-to-urban migration, natural population growth in urban areas, and the expansion of urban boundaries.
Rural-to-urban migration was particularly high during the Syrian Civil War, as people fled violence and insecurity in rural areas.
Natural population growth in urban areas was also a factor in the increase in the share of urban population.
The fertility rate in Syria is higher in urban areas than in rural areas, and urban areas have lower mortality rates.
The expansion of urban boundaries also contributed to the increase in the share of urban population in Syria.

There's a remarkable rise in the category of other independent living arrangements, from 4% in 1968 to 8% in 2007, followed by a significant jump to 23% in 2012.
The percentage of young adults living with other kin experienced fluctuations, with an increase from 3% in 1968 to 8% in 2007 and a slight reduction to 7% in 2012.
Overall, there has been a clear shift toward more young adults either living at home with their parents or in other independent living arrangements over the span of these 44 years.

The chart shows the monthly number of unemployed people in the United States from November 2019 to November 2020, in millions, adjusted.
The number of unemployed people increased sharply in April 2020, reaching a peak of 26.5 million in May 2020.
This was due to the COVID-19 pandemic, which led to widespread layoffs and business closures.
The number of unemployed people then began to decline, but remained elevated throughout 2020.
In November 2020, there were still 10.7 million unemployed people in the United States, which was 2.0 million higher than in November 2019.
The chart shows a clear relationship between the COVID-19 pandemic and the increase in unemployment.
The number of unemployed people began to increase sharply in April 2020, when the pandemic first hit the United States.
The number of unemployed people then peaked in May 2020, and began to decline slowly thereafter.
The chart also shows that the unemployment rate remained elevated throughout 2020, even though the number of unemployed people began to decline.
This is because the labor force participation rate also declined during this period, as many people left the workforce due to the pandemic.
The chart illustrates public opinion over time regarding the legal marriage of gays and lesbians.
The x-axis represents the years from 1996 to 2007, while the y-axis indicates the percentage of respondents who favor or oppose the notion, ranging from 27% to 65%.
Two trends are depicted: one for 'Favor' and one for 'Oppose'.
The 'Favor' trend, marked in blue, shows an initial percentage of 27% in 1996 that increases overall, reaching a peak of 60% in 2005 before declining slightly to 55% by 2007.
This shows a substantial rise in favorability over the 11-year period.
In contrast, the 'Oppose' trend, shown in orange, starts at a higher percentage of 65% in 1996.
It displays an overall declining trend with intermittent fluctuations, decreasing to its lowest point at 33% in 2007.
The highest opposition was recorded in the initial year, 1996, with a few peaks along the timeline, such as 63% opposition in 2004, just before a sharp decline to 51% in the following year.
Both trends clearly cross between the years 2004 and 2005, indicating that the number of people who favor gay and lesbian marriage surpassed those who oppose it during this period.
The intersection point suggests a significant shift in public opinion.

The chart shows the percentage of internet users who use online classified ads in 2005 and 2009, by demographic group.

Key Findings

 Overall use of online classified ads increased by 27% between 2005 and 2009.
Men are more likely than women to use online classified ads (28% vs. 25%).
Whites and Hispanics are more likely than Blacks to use online classified ads (27% and 28% vs. 26%).
Ages 18-29 and 30-49 are the most likely age groups to use online classified ads (30% and 30%, respectively).

People with lower levels of education and income are more likely to use online classified ads (24% and 23% for those with less than a high school diploma and household income below \$30,000, respectively).

Perceptual and Cognitive Phenomena

The chart is visually appealing and easy to understand.
The use of color and white space makes the data easy to scan, and the labels are clear and concise.
The chart also uses a consistent axis scale, which makes it easy to compare the data across different demographic groups.
One perceptual phenomenon that is evident in the chart is the peaking effect.

Figure: Majority of Americans say they are more apt to trust research when the data is openly available

Statistics:

 57% of Americans say they trust scientific research findings more if the researchers make their data publicly available.
34% of Americans say that makes no difference.
8% of Americans say they are less apt to trust research findings if the data is released publicly.

Relations:

 Open access to data is the factor that most increases public trust in research findings, with 57% of Americans saying it makes them trust research findings more.
Independent review of research findings also increases public trust, with 52% of Americans saying it makes them trust research findings more.
Industry funding is the factor that most decreases public trust in research findings, with 58% of Americans saying it makes them trust research findings less.

Extrema:

 The highest percentage of Americans (57%) say they trust scientific research findings more if the researchers make their data publicly available.
The lowest percentage of Americans (8%) say they trust research findings less if the data is released publicly.
The largest percentage of Americans (58%) say they trust scientific findings less if they know the research was funded by industry groups.

The line for controlling gun ownership starts at 57% in 1993 and reaches its peak in 1999 at 65%.
After 1999, this viewpoint sees a decline, falling to 54% in 2003, and then experiencing a slight increase to 58% in 2008, before dropping again to 50% in 2011.
In contrast, the line representing the view that it is more important to protect gun rights starts at 34% in 1993, showing a lower initial value compared to gun control.
It decreases further to 30% in 1999, marking the lowest point on the graph for this viewpoint.
However, from 1999 onwards, there is a rising trend, with percentages increasing to 42% in 2003 and to 37% in 2008, showing a brief dip.

By 2011, the percentage favoring the protection of gun rights rebounds to 46%, which is a significant increase from its lowest point and nearly equals the 50% of those favoring control of gun ownership.

The trend lines cross between 2008 and 2011, indicating that the gap between the two viewpoints has narrowed significantly, reflecting a divided opinion on the importance of controlling gun ownership versus protecting gun rights by 2011.

The chart displays data on the perceived importance of a spouse's religion in the decision to marry among individuals in different types of religious affiliations.
It is based on the 2014 Religious Landscape Study recontract survey conducted from March 17-May 6, 2015.

The categories of affiliation include all married people, both affiliated with the same religion, both affiliated but with different religions, one affiliated and one unaffiliated, and both unaffiliated.

For all married people, 27% consider the spouse's religion to be very important, 21% say it's somewhat important, and the largest group, 51%, feel it is not too or not at all important, with 1% not knowing.
Among spouses both affiliated with the same religion, 36% say it's very important, which is the highest percentage across all groups for considering a spouse's religion very important.

In contrast, those with different religious affiliations or who are unaffiliated place less importance on a spouse's religion: 18% of those with different religions and 10% of one affiliated and one unaffiliated deem it very important, while only 5% of both unaffiliated consider it very important.
The feeling that spouse's religion is not too or not at all important is most prevalent among the unaffiliated couples, at 84%, and least prevalent among those who share the same religion, at 37%.
The survey suggests a strong trend towards the insignificance of religious affiliation matching in marital decisions, especially in religiously mixed or unaffiliated couples.

The chart shows changes in teens' average daily time use in summer, from 2003-2007 to 2013-2017.

Socializing: Teens are spending less time socializing in the summer, with a decrease of 22 minutes per day.

On screens: Teens are spending less time on screens in the summer, with a decrease of 7 minutes per day.

Relationships

 The average number of deaths per day is higher in Republican districts than in Democratic districts.

The average number of deaths per day decreases as Republican vote share increases.

Conclusion

This chart shows that the political profile of congressional districts hard hit by COVID-19 has changed substantially since spring 2020.
Republican districts, particularly those with low Republican vote share, have been disproportionately affected by the virus.

The latest national survey by the Pew Research Center for the People & the Press, conducted 1973 among 1,000 interviews in the U.S., finds that 32% of the public has a great deal of confidence in U.S. leadership while 56% have a near a fair amount of confidence that the president.
There is considerable dissatisfaction with the way democracy is working in many countries.
Across the nations polled, a median of 52% are dissatisfied with how their democracy is working, while 44% are satisfied.
Greeks, Bulgarians and Nigerians register the highest levels of dissatisfaction.
In general, people with lower incomes and those who do not support the ruling party are more likely to be dissatisfied with the functioning of democracy.
Further, in many European countries, supporters of right-wing populist political parties are especially likely to hold this view.
Supporters of Poland’s Law and Justice Party and Hungary’s Fidesz Party – two governing populist parties – show the opposite pattern.
One way in which people are unhappy with the way democracy works is that they see political elites as out of touch.

Across the nations surveyed, a median of 64% disagree with the statement “Most elected officials care what people like me think.” This opinion is particularly widespread in Europe – a median of 69% express this view.
Further, 71% share this view in the U.S.
In contrast, fewer say this in the three Asian emerging economies included in the study: India (31%), the Philippines (29%) and Indonesia (18%).

The chart from the Pew Research Center presents statistics on U.S. adults' perceptions of what constitutes online harassment and which behaviors they believe should prompt social media platform intervention.
It stems from a scenario involving a woman, Julie, who experiences various forms of online negativity after posting a controversial political opinion.

Key findings include:
- The most agreed upon form of online harassment is Julie receiving threatening messages, with 86% of U.S. adults considering it harassment and 76% thinking it should be addressed by the social media platform.
- Editing Julie's picture to include sexual images is seen as harassment by 84% and warrants a platform response by 71%.
- Vulgar messages about Julie's looks and sexual behavior are considered harassment by 85% of adults, with 66% believing the platform should intervene.
- A lower percentage, 43% see unsolicited messages as harassment, and 20% believe it should prompt a platform response.
- When Julie's post is shared by a popular blogger, 17% consider it harassment, and 13% think it necessitates a platform response.
- Lastly, the scenario of Julie's friends disagreeing with her is seen as the least concerning, with only 3% considering it harassment and 2% suggesting that social media platforms should step in.

Chart Description

The chart shows the percentage of Americans who said that controlling gun ownership was more important than protecting the right of Americans to own guns, from 1993 to 2011.

Statistical Highlights

 The highest percentage of Americans who said controlling gun ownership was more important was 65%, in 1993.
The lowest percentage was 30%, in 2011.
There was a significant decrease in the percentage of Americans who said controlling gun ownership was more important between 1993 and 2011.

Perceptual and Cognitive Phenomena

The chart shows a clear trend of decreasing support for gun control over time.

This trend may be due to a number of factors, including:

 The rise of the gun rights movement in the United States
 The increasing polarization of American politics
 The perception that gun control measures are ineffective or even harmful

The chart also suggests that there is a significant partisan divide on the issue of gun control.
Democrats are much more likely than Republicans to say that controlling gun ownership is more important than protecting the right of Americans to own guns.
Overall, the chart shows that public opinion on gun control has become increasingly divided over time.

Additional Comments

It is important to note that the chart only shows the percentage of Americans who said controlling gun ownership was more important than protecting the right of Americans to own guns.
It does not show the percentage of Americans who support stricter gun control laws, or the percentage of Americans who believe that gun control is ineffective.

The graph shows the population density of Malaysia from 2000 to 2018, in people per square kilometer.
The population density increased steadily from 73.1 people per square kilometer in 2000 to 91.9 people per square kilometer in 2018.
This represents an increase of 25.5% over the 18-year period.
The population density of Malaysia is relatively high compared to other countries in Southeast Asia.

In 2018, the population density of Malaysia was higher than that of Indonesia (147 people per square kilometer), Thailand (135 people per square kilometer), and Vietnam (278 people per square kilometer).
However, the population density of Malaysia was lower than that of Singapore (8,309 people per square kilometer).
The population density of Malaysia is not evenly distributed throughout the country.
The most densely populated areas are located in the western part of Peninsular Malaysia, including the Klang Valley and the state of Selangor.
The least densely populated areas are located in the eastern states of Sabah and Sarawak.
The population density of Malaysia is expected to continue to increase in the coming years.
